Title: Anna Nicole Smith: You Don't Know Me
Description: From director Ursula Macfarlane (Untouchable) and producer Alexandra Lacey comes an unflinching and humanizing examination of the life, death and secrets of Vickie Lynn Hogan -- better known as model and actress Anna Nicole Smith. From her first appearance in Playboy in 1992, Anna Nicole's dizzying ascent was the very essence of the American dream, brought to a tragic halt with her untimely passing in 2007. With access to never-before-seen footage, home movies, and interviews with key figures who have not spoken out until now, ANNA NICOLE SMITH: YOU DON'T KNOW ME reveals new insights into the story of the quintessential blonde bombshell hardly anyone really knew.

Characteristics.Producer:: Alexandra Lacey

Reviews.Name: Kayleigh Donaldson
Reviews.Message: Is the point of this to show the pain Smith put herself through to achieve perfection? It just feels like yet another excuse to leer at someone who was gawked at from birth.

Reviews.Name: Richard Roeper
Reviews.Message: A solid and straightforward look at the life and times of the small-town Texas girl who for a time in the 1990s was as famous as just about anyone on the planet.

Reviews.Name: Randy Myers
Reviews.Message: Macfarlane’s sad portrait provides deeper context to the tragic life of the former stripper, model and actress.

Reviews.Name: Audra Heinrichs
Reviews.Message: You Don’t Know Me is Blonde-esque in that it fails to care why Smith might’ve felt the need to lie even before achieving fame, and later, infamy.

Reviews.Name: John Serba
Reviews.Message: It’s frustrating to watch You Don’t Know Me meander around the substance of Smith’s heart, her moral center, and come to a smudgy conclusion: It’s complicated!

Reviews.Name: Cady Lang
Reviews.Message: Ultimately more of a voyeuristic cautionary tale than an accounting of a complex woman’s humanity.

Reviews.Name: Calum Marsh
Reviews.Message: Smith deserved better than how she was treated. And she deserves better than this.

Reviews.Name: Amanda Guarragi
Reviews.Message: Apart from the new footage, this doesn’t expand on the story everyone knows.

Reviews.Name: Anna Bogutskaya
Reviews.Message: While a sub-genre of documentaries reassessing the maligned women of the Noughties is thriving, Anna Nicole Smith: You Don’t Know Me can barely contain its contempt for its subject matter.

Reviews.Name: Chris Vognar
Reviews.Message: It remains a visually engaging portrait that depicts Smith as more than just a little girl lost. The film argues that, despite a powerful self-destructive streak... she often knew exactly what she was doing.

Reviews.Name: Brian Lowry
Reviews.Message: While there are some new details in the telling, the net effect leaves the Smith that people didn't know, other than those meticulously airbrushed photo spreads, largely untouched.

Reviews.Name: Noel Murray
Reviews.Message: This is an in-depth film about a person many presumed had no depth at all.

Reviews.Name: Courtney Howard
Reviews.Message: This exploration and would-be exoneration of Anna Nicole Smith’s tragic life becomes the kind of exploitation it seeks to condemn.

Reviews.Name: Angie Han
Reviews.Message: You Don’t Know Me aims to cut past the mythology to reveal the flesh-and-blood woman underneath, and in doing so assembles a mostly sympathetic, mostly compelling portrait of an all-American tragedy.

Reviews.Name: Peter Bradshaw
Reviews.Message: It’s an effective retelling, though the film could have concentrated more on her tragicomic relationship with her oil plutocrat husband.

Reviews.Name: Susie Bright
Reviews.Message: “You Don’t Know Me” producers needed to be made of sterner stuff if they wanted a memorable picture.

Title: Assassin Club
Description: Henry Golding (G.I. JOE: SNAKE EYES) stars in this highly entertaining, globe-trotting action thriller. The hunter becomes the hunted when an elite assassin (Golding) is given his final contract: to kill seven people around the world -- only to discover the targets are equally skilled assassins hired to kill him. His only shot to survive is to uncover the mysterious mastermind behind the deadly plot before it's too late. Also starring Daniela Melchior (The Suicide Squad) with Noomi Rapace (Tom Clancy's Jack Ryan) and Sam Neill (Jurassic Park).

Characteristics.Producer:: Ellen S. Wander, Jordan Dykstra, Todd Lundbohm, Emanuele Moretti, Kieran Corrigan

Reviews.Name: Simon Abrams
Reviews.Message: While the ideal viewer of “Assassin Club” probably understands and accepts the limitations of this bottom-dollar time-waster, even the least choosy genre fans can do better.

Reviews.Name: Dennis Schwartz
Reviews.Message: It's a plodding film, moving along at an infuriating slow pace.

Reviews.Name: Sergio Pereira
Reviews.Message: Assassin Club isn't about to knock John Wick off his perch, but it is an entertaining, turn-off-the-brain movie in the same vein as other '90s classics like Assassins and Hard Target.

Reviews.Name: Nathaniel Muir
Reviews.Message: The pacing does not help as clunky narrative fill like little more than placeholders before the next big shootout. Assassin Club is never aggressively bad – there are even times when it exceeds expectations. But it also feels like a missed opportunity.

Reviews.Name: Roger Moore
Reviews.Message: In or out of action, Golding isn’t anybody’s idea of a big draw, and pitting him against “The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo” Rapace, and pairing him up with Neill as the upper class Brit who gives the assassin his assignments doesn’t change that.

Reviews.Name: Brian Orndorf
Reviews.Message: “Assassin Club” has trained hitmen on the run to murder one another, crossing the globe to do so, but the whole thing is just impossibly dull.

Reviews.Name: Jeffrey Lyles
Reviews.Message: Flawless in its ineptness, Assassin Club misses the mark of being an entertaining over the top action spy game with every shot.

Reviews.Name: Todd Jorgenson
Reviews.Message: With abundant visual razzle-dazzle trying to invigorate a pedestrian plot, this globetrotting thriller unfortunately squanders a talented cast.

Reviews.Name: Dan Tabor
Reviews.Message: Assassin Club is a pulpy actioner that eventually lives up to the movie you hoped it could be. It’s just the challenge of getting there, that might be too arduous for some.

Reviews.Name: Martin Unsworth
Reviews.Message: Assassin Club plods along from hit to hit. Long bouts of exposition that are directed with little flair or verve bring things to a snail’s pace, sadly.

Reviews.Name: Rich Cline
Reviews.Message: Not only is the plot jarringly generic, but the swerving camerawork turns the action into a dizzying mess. Meanwhile, director Camille Delamarre encourages the cast to play everything far over the top.

Reviews.Name: John Nugent
Reviews.Message: Incompetent and mostly just quite boring, Assassin Club doesn’t even have the good grace to be so-bad-it’s-good. Rough, rough stuff.

Reviews.Name: Xan Brooks
Reviews.Message: A rote whirl of shootouts, stakeouts and extended chases around Europe’s major cities.

Reviews.Name: Edward Porter
Reviews.Message: A dull potboiler that lumbers from one European city to another as various hired killers battle it out for murky reasons.

Reviews.Name: Kevin Maher
Reviews.Message: None of it holds together, the action scenes are tedious and Golding’s permanently constipated-looking Morgan spends far too much time driving around aimlessly in his souped-up Audi, searching, presumably, for an exit out of the movie.

Reviews.Name: Brian Viner
Reviews.Message: ... Desperately corny and derivative.

Reviews.Name: Maria Lattila
Reviews.Message: With a little more effort, love and care, Assassin Club could have been something. As it stands, it’s a missed opportunity and a truly torturous viewing experience

Reviews.Name: Eddie Harrison
Reviews.Message: …(Assassin Club) feels a lot like last decade’s model in terms of kick-ass thrills and espionage intrigue…

Reviews.Name: Mike McCahill
Reviews.Message: Everyone is travelling economy, with a tatty script stuffed way down, out of shame, in their carry-on luggage.

Title: Broadway
Description: Nelly has escaped from her wealthy and controlling family. As she dances in a strip club, she meets Markos, a small yet charismatic gangster, who helps her run away from her stepfather's henchmen. Markos soon becomes her protector and lover. He brings her into Broadway, Athens, an abandoned entertainment complex squatted by a small community of dancers, tramps, thieves and a captive monkey. For a while, everything goes well, even when Broadway hosts a mysterious man, injured and covered with bandages, wanted dead by Athens' most dangerous mafia. However, when Markos gets arrested and imprisoned, the newcomer will take an unexpectedly important place in the gang.

Characteristics.Producer:: Bertrand Gore, Amanda Livanou
Characteristics.Production Co:: Neda Film, Digital Cube, Blue Monday Productions

Reviews.Name: John Paul King
Reviews.Message: An ambitiously sweeping narrative that feels like equal parts film noir and Charles Dickens as it takes us into a colorful and morally ambiguous underworld...

Reviews.Name: Rich Cline
Reviews.Message: While the setting ripples with knowing details, the storytelling is awkward and elusive. And the film is never as transgressive as it pretends to be.

Reviews.Name: Avi Offer
Reviews.Message: Audacious and unconventional, but ultimately underwhelming and less than the sum of its many parts.

Reviews.Name: Kelli Weston
Reviews.Message: Amid some uneven characterizations, the cast enlivens “Broadway” with their compelling performances, sealed by a stirring finale and a characteristically soaring score from Gabriel Yared.

Reviews.Name: Gary M. Kramer
Reviews.Message: Broadway is entertaining when Massalas keeps the characters and the viewers guessing, but things get predictable once the story begins in earnest.... While the plotting is disappointing, the film looks great.

Reviews.Name: Dennis Harvey
Reviews.Message: An urban fantasia in the cult-cinema mode of Diva, Wings of Desire...

Reviews.Name: Roger Moore
Reviews.Message: Solidly suspenseful Greek film noir set among Athen pickpockets, men and a pole dancer laying low by night, putting on “shows” to distract their marks during the day...

Title: Giving Birth to a Butterfly
Description: After having her identity stolen online, Diana Dent leaves her family and goes on a road trip with her son's pregnant girlfriend to track down the perpetrators. The mismatched travel companions form an unexpected bond as they concede to the hardships of their own lives, and their hunt for answers becomes a surreal journey of self-discovery and empowerment.

Characteristics.Producer:: Daryl Freimark, Theodore Schaefer

Reviews.Name: Payton McCarty-Simas
Reviews.Message: While there is potential for poignancy in this (overtly) Homeric and surreal journey for self-acceptance, as it progresses, like its titular butterflies, the film ultimately gets lost in the breeze.

Reviews.Name: David Lynch
Reviews.Message: If “Giving Birth to a Butterfly” finds Schaefer in his own storytelling metamorphosis, it’s worth awaiting what he has to offer once fully emerged.

Reviews.Name: Noel Murray
Reviews.Message: Even for a movie meant to be offbeat, the rhythm is jarringly askew.

Reviews.Name: Beatrice Loayza
Reviews.Message: I hate to use “Lynchian,” a term frequently — and slovenly — invoked for films with a merely surrealist bent. But Schaefer’s film, also steeped in a distinctly American nostalgia, more than deserves the description.

Reviews.Name: Roger Moore
Reviews.Message: The entire enterprise feels like a piece of experimental theater that needs further workshopping before it’s ready for the stage.

Reviews.Name: Shelagh Rowan-Legg
Reviews.Message: While it's missing some connective tissue that would strengthen its American-style magical realism mode, there's a heartache and a hopefulness to Giving Birth to a Butterfly that makes for a compelling journey.

Reviews.Name: Alexandra Heller-Nicholas
Reviews.Message: Giving Birth to a Butterfly is a poem, a love song, a cry to be heard and a breaking free, all in one.

Reviews.Name: Morgan Rojas
Reviews.Message: A future cult classic given its artful take on transformation, both literal and figurative.

Reviews.Name: Katie Rife
Reviews.Message: Flimsy as it is, Giving Birth To A Butterfly shows promise.

Reviews.Name: Stephen Saito
Reviews.Message: Schaefer shrewdly lets the theatricality of the actors' work fall away as the the world around them looks more like a stage, cleverly conjuring the game of make believe that everyone plays in their daily lives.

Reviews.Name: Natasha Alvar
Reviews.Message: Beautiful and wonderfully poetic, the film acts like an interlude of sorts, as the viewer finds themselves basking in the imagery of two women at a crossroads in their lives.

Reviews.Name: Walter Chaw
Reviews.Message: As it is, it's one of those movies trying so hard for profundity that it's tough not to root for it--and tougher still to watch it fail.

Reviews.Name: Jared Mobarak
Reviews.Message: Giving Birth to a Butterfly becomes a road trip poem of its own reminding us that it's okay to stop, recalibrate, and change evolutionary course.

Reviews.Name: Jennie Kermode
Reviews.Message: It's a distinctive piece of work. Not everyone will be amused, yet it's rare to see a vision this complete successfully brought to life on film, and cult status seems to beckon as some viewers are swept off their feet.

Reviews.Name: Steven Warner
Reviews.Message: It ultimately feels like something Schaefer, like so many filmmakers before him, simply had to get out of his system.

Reviews.Name: Rob Aldam
Reviews.Message: Diane's blunt cynicism rubs up against Marlene's honest openness to create a fascinating and immersive viewing experience.

Reviews.Name: Jon Mendelsohn
Reviews.Message: Giving Birth to a Butterfly is more like a complicated poem than a fully realized film, but it's still original enough to warrant a first-time viewing.

Title: La Civil
Description: La Civil tells the story of Cielo, a mother in search of her daughter, abducted by  a criminal gang in Northern Mexico. As the authorities fail to offer support in the search, Cielo takes matters into her own hands. Cielo begins her own investigation and earns the trust and sympathy of Lamarque, an unconventional army Lieutenant working in the region. He agrees to help Cielo in her search, because her research data could be useful to his operations as well. Cielo's collaboration with Lamarque pulls her further into a vicious cycle of violence. The film focuses on Cielo’s emotional rollercoaster, as she is drawn into increasingly intense and dangerous circumstances. The camera stays close, we never lose sight of her as she gradually transforms from housewife into avenging activist. As events unfold, Cielo gets closer to the truth: discovering a mass grave, obtaining official DNA analyses, confronting one of the presumed kidnappers, but corruption and apathy keep her from finding resolution. Until the end finally comes, unpredictable and uninvited... The story was inspired by true events.

Characteristics.Producer:: Hans Everaert
Characteristics.Writer:: Teodora Ana Mihai, Habacuc Antonio De Rosario
Characteristics.Production Co:: Teorema Films, Les Films du Fleuve, Menuetto Film, Mobra Films, One For The Road

Reviews.Name: Claudia Puig
Reviews.Message: A very compelling cartel kidnapping drama.

Reviews.Name: Carlos Aguilar
Reviews.Message: [An] essential, if harrowing thriller...

Reviews.Name: Filipe Freitas
Reviews.Message: [Mihai] narrative mechanics never weigh down the power of the story, which works as a social chronicle of a country ravaged by violence and corruption.

Reviews.Name: Paddy Mulholland
Reviews.Message: There’s little objectively wrong with this cartel kidnapping drama but there’s also little objectively new. Fine filmmaking that’s rarely any more than just fine.

Reviews.Name: Alessandra Rangel
Reviews.Message: Sometimes a thriller, and always a harrowing drama, La civil is painful to watch because it perfectly captures the disenchantment...

Reviews.Name: Sumner Forbes
Reviews.Message: La Civil is a dense and meticulously crafted drama.

Reviews.Name: Lee Jutton
Reviews.Message: La Civil is ultimately an uneven crime thriller carried by an exceptional actress. Still, its subject matter is so important, and certain moments so impactful, that one is almost inclined to overlook its weaknesses. Almost.

Reviews.Name: Todd Jorgenson
Reviews.Message: This raw and unflinching thriller infuses genre tropes with rich cultural specificity and gut-wrenching emotional complexity.

Reviews.Name: Glenn Kenny
Reviews.Message: A movie that grabs you by the heart quickly and doesn’t let up the stress for any significant amount of time.

Reviews.Name: Kyle Smith
Reviews.Message: From the production design to the flat dialogue to the fly-on-the-wall camera work, everything about the film is utterly naturalistic and completely convincing. With Ms. Ramírez setting the tone, the cast is chillingly believable.

Reviews.Name: Avi Offer
Reviews.Message: An engrossing, unflinching and suspenseful thriller anchored by Arcelia Ramírez gives a raw and bravura performance.

Reviews.Name: A.O. Scott
Reviews.Message: The demoralization that afflicts Cielo casts a shadow on the audience, whose capacity for compassion may reach its limit even before the full measure of her suffering has been taken.

Reviews.Name: Hugo Hernández Valdivia
Reviews.Message:
The possibilities of taking justice into one's own hands not only carry enormous risk, but also inevitably involve blood spattering.
[Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Erick Estrada
Reviews.Message: Without denying the good intentions of the film, there is a conceptual mismatch that detracts from the possibility of extracting a more critical discourse that, in the situation in which we live, I consider indispensable. [Full review in Spanish[

Reviews.Name: Carlos Bonfil
Reviews.Message: Arcelia Ramírez gives her maternal character a moral complexity, unusual in this type of story, which is, in short, the most substantial attraction of the film. [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Message:

Reviews.Message: The mother of an abducted teenager becomes a Woman on Fire on Mexico's mean streets in this brutal cartel thriller.

Title: Out and About
Description: "Out and About" is an unconventional tale about a middle-aged man trying to come to terms with his life over the course of an afternoon walk through his hometown. Distinctive in both style and substance and told virtually in real time, the story weaves together the protagonist's inner monologue with conversations he has with the people he encounters along the way. Raw, brutally honest, poignant and funny, "Out and About" explores the contrast between our inner and outer selves, the conflict between old dreams and new realities, and one man's search for meaning as he wrestles with aging, success and failure in America, and his ultimate place in the world.

Characteristics.Producer:: Ivon Visalli, Konstantin Von Krusenstiern
Characteristics.Production Co:: Sugar Pond Films, Changing Film Productions

Reviews.Name: Tony Asankomah
Reviews.Message: Callahan's script delves into the contradictions and imperfections of everyday life, exploring the dichotomy between our internal thoughts and the image we project to the outside world.

Reviews.Name: Gerald Peary
Reviews.Message: I commend Callahan for having the guts to enthrall an audience with a virtually plotless movie.

Reviews.Name: Robin Clifford
Reviews.Message: The writer-director-actor-star is not a household name for most of us, but his assured hold on the helm and his character’s interesting reflections on life make me want to see more – both in front of and behind the screen.

Reviews.Name: Josh Bell
Reviews.Message: Spending 83 minutes in this dude's head is an insufferable experience, and the people around him aren't much more tolerable.

Reviews.Name: Laura Clifford
Reviews.Message: Now here is a little movie that deserves a big audience.  This winner of three regional U.S. film festivals takes the simple premise of a walk in real time and turns it into a rumination on life…a must see gem.

Title: Zarna Garg: One in a Billion

Reviews.Name: Sean L. McCarthy
Reviews.Message: Much of Garg’s act focuses on the advantages of being practical as a parent, rather than encouraging kids to follow their dreams.

Title: Faithfully Yours
Description: Using each other as alibis, two friends sneak off to indulge in secret affairs, but their elaborate web of lies unravels when one of them goes missing.

Characteristics.Producer:: Rachel Van Bommel
Characteristics.Writer:: Elisabeth Lodeizen, Paul Jan Nelissen, André van Duren

Reviews.Name: John Serba
Reviews.Message: Van Duren makes a halfway decent attempt to build some paranoid suspense as Bodil sniffs out others’ secrets as she tries to conceal her own, but the endeavor is frustratingly generic, and increasingly absurd...

Reviews.Name: Jason Flatt
Reviews.Message: Really there is little redeeming or worthwhile about Faithfully Yours. Just don’t watch it. Even by the time it gets to the end and two reasonable twists take place, it’s already far too late for them to redeem what is just entirely dull from the onset.

Reviews.Name: Roger Moore
Reviews.Message: A subtly-acted slow-starter, with a fine, flashy finish, a “solid” genre piece that never quite crosses over into riveting.

Title: Queenmaker: The Making of an It Girl
Description: In the height of heiress-era NYC, an anonymous blogger infiltrated Manhattan's elite, bringing socialite celebrities to new heights; when the website's creator was unmasked, the mastermind was not who anybody expected.

Reviews.Name: Chris Vognar
Reviews.Message: Rose’s story and its past connection to the celebrity world of status and image open up a world of ideas regarding identity -- its symbolism, its fluidity, and its very meaning.

Reviews.Name: Radhika Menon
Reviews.Message: The documentary tries to tell too many stories and ends up not telling any of them completely.

Reviews.Name: Coleman Spilde
Reviews.Message: Though certainly disappointing, the film is still a uniquely mystifying look at a bygone era that will satisfy those who were steeped in its libelous thrills.

Reviews.Name: Glenn Kenny
Reviews.Message: The sleight of hand Drucker uses... delivers its particulars with a wallop. And the finale is as compassionate as it is sad and unnerving.

Reviews.Name: Noel Murray
Reviews.Message: There’s a strong point of view here, as Drucker scrutinizes an era that established a lot of the codes and aspirations of our own influencer-saturated times.

Title: Fanfic
Description: Two high school students form an intense connection as they navigate the challenges of discovering and expressing their truest selves.

Reviews.Name: Roger Moore
Reviews.Message: The best film in ages about coming to grips with “fluid” gender issues so dominating film, TV and other media these days is smart, reassuringly sweet and Polish.

Reviews.Name: John Serba
Reviews.Message: It’s more welterweight than heavyweight ; it’s also a hopeful story instead of a traumatic one, and all the more endearing for it.

Title: The Haunting of Hell Hole Mine
Description: Inside a long-abandoned gold mine, lurks the Shakani, a dark supernatural being conjured by the Shanowah tribe ages ago to defeat their enemies. Not only ferocious and fast, but can appear as anyone and get inside your mind. Luke's ancestors trapped it in the mine but each has also gone crazy. Now Luke's niece Poni, has come down with "the family curse." But Luke believes with the proper medical treatment she can be healed if only he can get the money to pay for it. So with a couple friends he tries his luck at the gold mine but gradually realizes he must defeat the Shakani and end the family curse.

Title: White Men Can't Jump
Description: From 20th Century Studios, the all-new comedy "White Men Can't Jump" is a modern remix of the iconic 1992 film that celebrates the streetball hustling culture of Los Angeles. Multi-platinum rap superstar Jack Harlow makes his movie debut as Jeremy, a former star of the game whose injuries stalled his career, and Sinqua Walls stars as Kamal, once a promising player who derailed his own future in the sport. Juggling tenuous relationships, financial pressures and serious internal struggles, the two ballers--opposites who are seemingly miles apart--find they might have more in common than they imagined possible.

Characteristics.Producer:: Kenya Barris, Paul Hall
Characteristics.Production Co:: Khalabo Ink Society, Mortal Media, 20th Century Studios

Reviews.Name: James Croot
Reviews.Message: Even the Air Bud franchise offered better basketball entertainment than this farrago.

Reviews.Name: Kevin Carr
Reviews.Message: Bland, spiritless and dull, this features characters that are irritating at best and unforgettable at worst.

Reviews.Name: Brian Lowry
Reviews.Message: At its best this White Men Can’t Jump conveys the fragility of hoop dreams, while tackling what former players do with their lives once the promise of signing bonuses and sponsorship deals appears to have fizzled.

Reviews.Name: Fico Cangiano
Reviews.Message: Not even the "basketball" in White Men Can't Jump can save this airball of a remake. Devoid of any of the charm, jokes or performances that made the original work. Pass. [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Rachel Leishman
Reviews.Message: It’s easy to bring a friendship to life onscreen. The challenge is making your audience care about it, and White Men Can’t Jump manages to make Jeremy and Kamal’s friendship something worth watching.

Reviews.Name: John Serba
Reviews.Message: The film is by no means an inspired reinvention of the original, but it gives us two guys worth rooting for, and sometimes, that’s enough.

Reviews.Name: Ferdosa Abdi
Reviews.Message: White Men Can’t Jump is failed by the inadequacies of its creative team, as it's not funny enough to justify its existence nor poignant enough.

Reviews.Name: Luke Y. Thompson
Reviews.Message: Weak Remakes Don’t Soar

Reviews.Name: Edward Porter
Reviews.Message: The film-maker known simply as Calmatic has directed a genial but easily forgotten movie.

Reviews.Name: Robert Daniels
Reviews.Message: The film is as unimaginative as it is corny, as dull as it is cheap, and as unfulfilling as any cash grab for a well-known property could be.

Reviews.Name: Jason Fraley
Reviews.Message: While the gameplay is realistic, the format is less immersive with 5-on-5 basketball. The 2-on-2 tournament was better at showing the bond between the two heroes as Billy and Sidney couldn’t rely on three other teammates; they had to rely on each other.

Reviews.Name: Chris Vognar
Reviews.Message: The new movie feels about as genuine as a bad team claiming innocence as it tanks for lottery position.

Reviews.Name: Todd Jorgenson
Reviews.Message: Coasting on the authentic rapport of its two stars and some convincing hoops action, the film softens the edges of the original without taking the material in a meaningful new direction.

Reviews.Name: Nina Metz
Reviews.Message: Hoop dreams, indeed.

Reviews.Name: Nate Adams
Reviews.Message: An airless, Disneyfied remake meant to jumpstart rapper Jack Harlow’s acting career, the modern day spin of “White Men Can’t Jump” makes for a pretty lousy game of basketball.

Reviews.Name: Jeffrey Lyles
Reviews.Message: Very much has its own vibe that makes for an unexpectedly pleasant surprise and a huge win for remake fans.

Reviews.Name: Casey Chong
Reviews.Message: A decent but bloated remake of 1992 basketball-comedy classic.

Reviews.Name: Alan French

Title: Robots
Description: Charles is a womanizer while Elaine is a gold-digger. The duo learn humanity when forced to team up and pursue robot doubles of themselves.

Characteristics.Producer:: Cassian Elwes, Julien Favre, Stephen Hamel, Lars Sylvest

Reviews.Name: Brian Orndorf
Reviews.Message: Christensen and Hines don’t have a vision for cinematic silliness, creating a terrible episode of television instead.

Reviews.Name: Mark Dujsik
Reviews.Message: [T]he movie is mostly defined by its lack of insight, foresight, and any ability to see how poorly imagined and executed the attempted humor here is.

Reviews.Name: Carla Hay
Reviews.Message: Robots with artificial intelligence could have come up with a better movie than the filmmakers responsible for the drab and unfunny comedy Robots, an embarrassing dud that fails to blend sci-fi and romance into an interesting story.

Title: Outpost
Description: An abused woman gets a job as a fire lookout in the mountains of northern Idaho, hoping the peaceful solitude will heal her trauma. However, the PTSD and isolation have other plans, and it's suddenly a fight to save herself and the town.

Characteristics.Producer:: Kara Baker, Joe Lo Truglio, Joe Mortimer

Reviews.Name: Crockett Houghton
Reviews.Message: The problem with Outpost is that it turned our survivor of something horrible into a murderer with no redeeming qualities. A swing and a miss.

Reviews.Name: Brian Tallerico
Reviews.Message: A film that’s too choppy and ridiculous for too long for its gut-punch of a final act to really connect.

Reviews.Name: Kimberley Elizabeth
Reviews.Message: [Outpost] ventures into the dark corners of the human psyche while delivering an unforgettable survival horror experience.

Reviews.Name: Mark Dujsik
Reviews.Message: It's difficult to imagine a less thoughtful and empathetic way to tell the underlying story of Outpost.

Reviews.Name: Aaron Neuwirth
Reviews.Message: While it’s of little surprise for me to once again see a comedic performer transfer their sense of tension and timing to the world of horror, I can say that I was ultimately won over thanks to having a cast full of character actors.

Reviews.Name: Carson Timar
Reviews.Message: While Outpost proves Joe Lo Truglio's ability within the horror genre and successfully overcomes many of the common faults in the genre, the film fails itself and its own characters with a beyond-questionable final act.

Reviews.Name: Brent McKnight
Reviews.Message: 'Outpost' has lofty aims and takes big swings. Though not all of them land and it never quite reaches the possible highs, this is a hell of a debut.

Reviews.Name: Brian Orndorf
Reviews.Message: A little uneven, but Lo Truglio captures the mental quake of trauma reasonably well, getting the endeavor on its feet with some degree of success.

Reviews.Name: Melissa Hannon
Reviews.Message: While Outpost may tell a familiar tale of survival, this elevated indie is a solid entry in the psychological horror subgenre. Fans will always love (Joe Lo) Truglio for his comedic roles, but let's hope he has more horror up his sleeve.

Reviews.Name: Tim Brennan
Reviews.Message: The fact remains that Joe Lo Truglio is a new voice in horror, one that’s thoughtful when necessary and always committed to going for your guts.

Reviews.Name: Joel Harley
Reviews.Message: While the film never quite reaches the heights it aims for, this striking debut makes a solid platform for its director’s genre aspirations.

Reviews.Name: Anton Bitel
Reviews.Message: ...an ordeal of endurance as much mental as physical, where victimhood is not just overcome but inverted. This is a glorious calling card – sensitive to sympathetic characterisation, yet unafraid, when the time is right, to call in the nasty exploitation

Title: Come Out Fighting
Description: Set during WWII, in this military adventure, a small, specialized squad of U.S. Army African American soldiers are sent on an unofficial rescue mission behind enemy lines to locate their missing commanding officer. The squad upon battling their way through the German defenses encounter more than they bargain for when they locate a downed U.S. Army fighter pilot. With the help of their friends at the 761st tank battalion, known as "The Black Panthers," the squad must find a way to survive and make it back in one piece.

Characteristics.Producer:: Dean Bloxom, Andre Relis, Steven Luke
Characteristics.Production Co:: Redbox Automated Retail, Lionsgate, Schuetzle Company Productions, VMI Worldwide

Reviews.Name: Mike McGranaghan
Reviews.Message: A movie about the contribution of African-Americans in WWII could be both important and stirring. Come Out Fighting is neither.

Reviews.Name: Julian Roman
Reviews.Message: Come Out Fighting has good intentions but struggles to be rousing and cinematic. Moments of genuine camaraderie are muddied by low-budget visual effects, questionable editing, and poorly defined, generic Nazi antagonists.

Reviews.Name: Calum Marsh
Reviews.Message: [Luke's] writing is thin and tends regularly toward platitudes, with characters spouting wisdom like “the cards have to fall where they fall.”

Reviews.Name: Brian Orndorf
Reviews.Message: It’s not all disappointing, as the feature shows some signs of life, but there’s a better, more stirring effort to be made about the subject.

Title: Asterix & Obelix: The Middle Kingdom
Description: Gallic heroes and forever friends Asterix and Obelix journey to China to help Princess Sa See save the Empress and her land from a nefarious prince.

Characteristics.Producer:: Yohan Baiada, Alain Attal
Characteristics.Production Co:: Just Bridge Entertainment, Pathé, Trésor Films, Les Enfants Terribles

Reviews.Name: Dhaval Roy
Reviews.Message: The film is driven by rib-tickling moments, high production value and a fresh story, but it’s best viewed independent of the iconic comic book series. It’s a family entertainer for those who don’t mind a slightly slow-paced watch...

Reviews.Name: Whang Yee Ling
Reviews.Message: There are few bright spots in this Gaul-ling retelling of a beloved comic book.

Reviews.Name: Pablo Vázquez
Reviews.Message: ... Fine tunes the broad strokes of the rescuable past films without reneging on their merits. [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Randy Meeks
Reviews.Message: After five movies, it's time to be realistic and hang up the sword: live-action doesn't work for a character that's so dependent on drawing such as Asterix.  [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Carlos Marañón
Reviews.Message: Lellouche's Obelix gobbles up the healthy version of Asterix. [Full review in Spanish]

Title: Consecration
Description: In CONSECRATION, after the suspicious death of her brother, a priest, Grace (Jena Malone) goes to the Mount Saviour Convent in Scotland to find out what really happened. Once there, she uncovers murder, sacrilege and a disturbing truth about her own past.

Characteristics.Producer:: Laurie Cook, Casey Herbert, Xavier Marchand, Jason Newmark
Characteristics.Production Co:: AGC Studios, Moonriver Content, Bigscope Films

Reviews.Name: Sean P. Means
Reviews.Message: The movie looks good, which is why it’s even more disappointing that the story is only held together by the flimsiest of movie tropes — the one where the central figure doesn’t know or suspect the truth that everyone around her clearly knows.

Reviews.Name: Sr. Rose Pacatte
Reviews.Message: A muddled attempt with no saving grace to tell a story about demonic action at a convent.

Reviews.Name: Kat Hughes
Reviews.Message: An enigmatic tale of finding one’s true identity and calling, Consecration’s fresh ideas are held together by yet another well-composed performance from Jena Malone.

Reviews.Name: Nikki Baughan
Reviews.Message: While Consecration leans heavily into the familiar cliches of holy horror, there’s some intriguing psychology at play; even if the film perhaps takes a little too long to reveal its most interesting aspects.

Reviews.Name: Wade Major
Reviews.Message: There are a lot of horror clichés here, but it does go to a place that I thought was a bit different. So I give it credit for that.

Reviews.Name: Lena Wilson
Reviews.Message: For those easily swayed by blood, nuns, and Jena Malone — i.e., those with good taste — there’s plenty of that to go around.

Reviews.Name: Jenn Adams
Reviews.Message: Set in a Scottish convent, Smith makes the most of a spooky setting. A unique premise, but an uneven execution cuts the knees out from under the narrative leaving us with a religious ghost story that feels by turns both terrifying and silly.

Reviews.Name: Alan Zilberman
Reviews.Message: Consecration does not add to the tradition of scary nuns, as it lacks the conviction or imagination to consider the depths of unhinged piety.

Reviews.Name: Lex Briscuso
Reviews.Message: Unfortunately, the movie’s worst enemy is its structure.

Reviews.Name: David Nusair
Reviews.Message: ...an utterly worthless endeavor that feels much, much longer than its 91 minutes.

Reviews.Name: Dennis Harvey
Reviews.Message: Why, at age 84, she chose to make a glowering Mother Superior her first film role in a decade is anyone’s guess.

Reviews.Name: Abbie Bernstein
Reviews.Message: A religious folk horror thriller that does an admirable job of putting us in its protagonist’s shoes.

Reviews.Name: Jennie Kermode
Reviews.Message: It’s good to see that Smith is still willing to risk biting off more than he can chew.

Reviews.Name: Keith Garlington
Reviews.Message: It's bookended by a promising premise that both starts and ends in an interesting place. But it's the sluggish middle that may have enough going on to hold your attention, but that never takes the story...in any exciting directions.

Reviews.Name: Dennis Schwartz
Reviews.Message: A doomed Catholic themed psychological horror film.

Reviews.Name: Noel Murray
Reviews.Message: When the threat the characters are facing remains so vague for so long, it robs the story of tension. It doesn’t help that Smith keeps the horror elements to a minimum, or that the picture is so drably colored and dimly lit.

Reviews.Name: Owen Gleiberman
Reviews.Message: Through it all... “Consecration” grows increasingly murky and blood-drenched and contrived.

Reviews.Name: James Verniere
Reviews.Message: The writers toss out a dozen story threads and manage to get them so tangled up you might not know what the film is about.

Reviews.Name: Natalia Keogan
Reviews.Message: It handles too many threads—childhood tragedy, murder cover-ups, clandestine spiritual rites—without the dexterity to effectively weave them together.

Reviews.Name: Ferdosa Abdi
Reviews.Message: As bloodied and haunted as it gets, Consecration is a somewhat satisfying journey because Smith and Cook's script understands Grace is the anchor.

Title: Mercy
Description: Leah Gibson (Jessica Jones), Jonathan Rhys Meyers (Vikings) and Academy Award® Winner Jon Voight (Coming Home) star in this action-packed thriller. An ex-military doctor finds herself in a deadly battle for survival when the Irish mafia seize control of the hospital at which she works. When her son is taken hostage, she is forced to rely upon her battle-hardened past and lethal skills after realizing there's no one left to save the day but her.

Characteristics.Producer:: Charles Cooper

Reviews.Name: Jeffrey M. Anderson
Reviews.Message: This "Die Hard in a hospital" action movie almost works; it's lean and efficient, but it's also just a little bit too ridiculous and fatally un-self-aware.

Reviews.Name: Gary M. Kramer
Reviews.Message: The B-movie Mercy, about an escalating hostage situation that unfolds in a hospital, contains plenty of fights, gun violence, and explosions, but it is hardly edge-of-your-seat stuff.

Reviews.Name: Avi Offer
Reviews.Message: A dull, lackluster and monotonous B-movie.

Reviews.Name: Brian Orndorf
Reviews.Message: Director Smith doesn’t have the pace or the right amount of punishment with the endeavor, which goes too soft too quickly, unable to shake its low-budget limitations.

Title: Kathal: A Jackfruit Mystery
Description: When two prized jackfruits disappear from a politician's garden, a spirited police officer's investigation takes an unexpected turn as she digs for the truth.

Characteristics.Producer:: Achin Jain, Ekta Kapoor, Shobha Kapoor, Guneet Monga

Title: The Thief Collector
Description: It was one of the most audacious and puzzling art thefts of a generation; In 1985, Willem de Kooning's seminal work, "Woman Ochre," was sliced from it's frame and stolen from the walls of an Arizona art museum, disappearing into the desert. Over thirty years later, in a remote town in New Mexico, the $160 million dollar painting was rediscovered in the unlikeliest of places.

Characteristics.Producer:: Caryn Capotosto, Jill Latiano, Joshua A. Kunau
Characteristics.Production Co:: Roots Productions, Diamond Docs, Museum & Crane, XTR

Reviews.Name: Alan French
Reviews.Message: The Thief Collector is wildly entertaining and features some of the funniest reenactments of the year.

Reviews.Name: Jared Mobarak
Reviews.Message: This is an utterly transfixing story told with an infectious tone, but it's about 80% speculation. And while that speculation is fun, the whole can feel like spinning wheels for long passages.

Reviews.Name: Mark Dujsik
Reviews.Message: [M]uch of Allison Otto's documentary ... amounts to a lot of speculation.

Reviews.Name: Mel Valentin
Reviews.Message: Ultimately, however, The Thief Collector confirms one of Citizen Kane’s grand themes, the unknowability of human personality. When the Sadlers left this world for the next, they took several, unrecoverable secrets with them.

Reviews.Name: Jordan Raup
Reviews.Message: With its whirlwind, surface-level observations of fascinatingly complex lives, it's the kind of scattershot true-crime documentary that grips in the moment but, with reflection, is more entertaining to discuss than revisit for additional clues.

Reviews.Name: Noel Murray
Reviews.Message: Allison Otto’s snappy documentary “The Thief Collector” ponders how and why the Alters got away with their one famous crime — and perhaps many more.

Reviews.Name: Liz Whittemore
Reviews.Message: Allison Otto brings audiences one of the most audacious modern-day stories of crime and passion. Part art history, part true crime, all intrigue, The Thief Collector is tailor-made for mystery lovers and cinephiles alike

Reviews.Name: Sherin Nicole
Reviews.Message: The Alters could rival Audrey Hepburn and Peter O’Toole in How to Steal a Million. After all, they did it. They got away with it too (but you’re not going to believe how).

Reviews.Name: Pam Grady
Reviews.Message: Out of a brazen act of theft, filmmaker Allison Otto fashions an indelible, all-American tale of life, larceny, and the pursuit of adventure,

Reviews.Name: Loren King
Reviews.Message: The Collector Thief is one of the most bizarre and intriguing of stranger-than-fiction documentaries, combining art heist and double lives.  It turns creepily pitch black and more incredulous than the most Coen of Coen brothers movies.

Reviews.Name: Leslie Combemale
Reviews.Message: Allison Otto’s doc goes unexpected places, far beyond a simple examination of one stolen masterpiece. This documentary reminds viewers the fun folks next door may be way more than they seem.

Reviews.Name: Jennifer Merin
Reviews.Message: The true story is astonishing, and Allison Otto’s take on it entails introduction of all the quirky characters, their psychological profiles, crime thriller plot twists and solid art history. The Thief Collector is solid entertainment.

Reviews.Name: Betsy Bozdech
Reviews.Message: The Alters’ story takes some unexpectedly dark turns, but overall The Thief Collector is breezy and fun.

Reviews.Name: Jennie Kermode
Reviews.Message: What begins as a spirited romp goes to dark places before it’s done

Reviews.Name: Todd Jorgenson
Reviews.Message: ... compiles a fascinating glimpse into broader notions of art appreciation and the peculiarities of human nature.

Reviews.Name: Cath Clarke
Reviews.Message: If nothing else, this documentary ought to give someone working in television the idea of making a detective series about house clearance experts.

Reviews.Name: Dennis Schwartz
Reviews.Message: Unusually interesting film, even if it has nothing to say that is definitive about the theft.

Reviews.Name: Warren Cantrell
Reviews.Message: Although it might have been nice to dig deeper  for example, a more thorough investigation into the Alter children  Otto and "The Thief Collector" seem to understand that an absence of answers is what makes this particular story so interesting.

Reviews.Name: Owen Gleiberman
Reviews.Message: A movie that has used art to touch something essential about how strangers — or maybe I should just say the downright strange — walk among us.

Reviews.Name: Allison Shoemaker
Reviews.Message: An entertaining and surprisingly suspenseful story of art, compulsion, chance and audacity.

Title: National Theatre Live: Best of Enemies
Description: In 1968 America, as two men fight to become the next president, all eyes are on the battle between two others: the cunningly conservative William F. Buckley Jr., and the unruly liberal Gore Vidal. During a new nightly television format, they debate the moral landscape of a shattered nation. As beliefs are challenged and slurs slung, a new frontier in American politics is opening and television news is about to be transformed forever. Jeremy Herrin (All My Sons) directs this blistering political thriller, filmed live in London's West End.

Title: Victim/Suspect
Description: On her first solo investigation, journalist Rae de Leon travels nationwide to uncover a shocking pattern: Young women tell the police they've been sexually assaulted, but instead of finding justice, they're charged with the crime of making a false report, arrested, and even imprisoned by the system they believed would protect them.

Characteristics.Producer:: Christopher Clements, Rachel De Leon, Julie Goldman, Alice Henty, Amanda Pike, Nancy Schwartzman
Characteristics.Production Co:: Center for Investigative Repor, Motto Pictures

Reviews.Name: Brianna Zigler
Reviews.Message: Victim/Suspect manages to be at once fascinating, improperly focused and somewhat redundant.

Reviews.Name: Louisa Moore
Reviews.Message: An artless documentary that feels overwritten and orchestrated to a fault. The topic is important and infuriating, but it’s not a particularly well-made film.

Reviews.Name: Kent Turner
Reviews.Message: [A] powerful, hard-hitting investigative documentary.

Reviews.Name: Sheri Flanders
Reviews.Message: This documentary doesn’t offer much in terms of craft, but one could perhaps make the argument that the subject matter necessitates no-frills storytelling that soberly focuses on facts and video evidence.

Reviews.Name: Juan Carlos Ugarelli
Reviews.Message: A revealing study on two sides of journalism: the tabloid press that accuses without evidence and sows disinformation, further stigmatizing these women; and investigative journalism that digs into minefields... [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Dwight Brown
Reviews.Message: It’s easy to feel overwhelmed with sadness and empathy for the victims. Easy to feel proud that a young reporter and documentarian turned wrong into right. That takes courage.

Reviews.Name: Brian Tallerico
Reviews.Message: [Victim/Suspect] suffers from the Netflix brand of overproduction, looking just a little too flashy and sinking everything with voiceover and interview sound bites that have been scripted to death.

Reviews.Name: Barbara Goslawski
Reviews.Message: Yes, the film generates a sense of the anger at the system that has perpetrated this injustice but not enough to warrant much further thought or even action.

Reviews.Name: Cory Woodroof
Reviews.Message: A very solid, depressing piece of accessible documentary journalism about a very troubling trend.

Reviews.Name: Katie Smith-Wong
Reviews.Message: A heartbreaking but eye-opening piece of filmmaking.

Reviews.Name: Sheri Linden
Reviews.Message: Measured and sometimes muddled, but unquestionably important.

Reviews.Name: Sebastian Zavala Kahn
Reviews.Message: A strong, powerful documentary that, despite feeling a tad neat and cold at times, benefits from De Leon's presence. And most importantly: it is a film that will remain engraved in your memories for a long time. Full review in Spanish.

Reviews.Name: Sarah Bea Milner
Reviews.Message: An upsetting documentary.

Reviews.Name: Andrew Parker
Reviews.Message: Victim/Suspect ends up being a vital and eye opening examination of widespread injustice that still leaves a lot on the table thanks to its strangely narrow focus.

Reviews.Name: Lena Wilson
Reviews.Message: You may need to take a month-long depression nap after you finish watching it, but this documentary will stick with you.

Reviews.Name: Kate Erbland
Reviews.Message: It’s all so very sober, so deeply sobering, that when actual emotion pops, that’s what jars. It shouldn’t be the case -- all of this should rattle us and move us into action.

Reviews.Name: Fran Hoepfner
Reviews.Message: That these stories are worth being told is inarguable, but is this the proper lens to go about it?

Title: The Little Mermaid
Description: The youngest of King Triton's daughters, and the most defiant, Ariel longs to find out more about the world beyond the sea, and while visiting the surface, falls for the dashing Prince Eric. While mermaids are forbidden to interact with humans, Ariel must follow her heart. She makes a deal with the evil sea witch, Ursula, which gives her a chance to experience life on land, but ultimately places her life -- and her father's crown -- in jeopardy.

Characteristics.Producer:: Marc Platt, Lin-Manuel Miranda, John DeLuca, Rob Marshall
Characteristics.Production Co:: 5000 Broadway Productions, Walt Disney Pictures, Lucamar, Marc Platt Productions

Title: About My Father
Description: The hottest comic in America, Sebastian Maniscalco joins forces with legendary Italian-American and two-time Oscar winner, Robert De Niro, in the new comedy ABOUT MY FATHER. The film centers around Sebastian (Maniscalco) who is encouraged by his fiancée (Leslie Bibb) to bring his immigrant, hairdresser father, Salvo (De Niro), to a weekend get-together with her super-rich and exceedingly eccentric family (Kim Cattrall, Anders Holm, Brett Dier, David Rasche). The weekend develops into what can only be described as a culture clash, leaving Sebastian and Salvo to discover that the great thing about family is everything about family.

Characteristics.Producer:: Andrew Miano, Paul Weitz, Chris Weitz, Judi Marmel

Title: The Machine
Description: Bert Kreischer rose to fame as a stand-up comedian known as The Machine, and in his signature set he recounts his true experience with Russian mobsters while on a booze-soaked college trip. Now, 23 years later, that trip has come back to haunt him as he and his estranged father (Mark Hamill) are kidnapped back to Russia by the mob to atone for something they say he did. Together, Bert and his father must retrace the steps of his younger self (Jimmy Tatro) in the midst of a war within a sociopathic crime family, all while attempting to find common ground in their often fraught relationship.

Characteristics.Rating:: R (Some Sexual References|Pervasive Language|Drug Use|Strong Violence)
Characteristics.Producer:: Bert Kreischer, LeeAnn Kreischer, Judi Marmel, Cale Boyter, Peter Atencio

Title: Kandahar
Description: An undercover CIA operative gets stuck in hostile territory in Afghanistan after his mission is exposed. Accompanied by his translator, he must fight enemy combatants as he tries to reach an extraction point in Kandahar.

Characteristics.Producer:: Basil Iwanyk, Brendon Boyea, Erica Lee, Gerard Butler, Alan Siegel, Christian Mercuri, Scott LaStaiti
Characteristics.Production Co:: MBC Studios, Thunder Road Pictures, Capstone Studios, G-BASE

Title: You Hurt My Feelings
Description: Beth (Julia Louis-Dreyfus), a popular writer, and her husband Don, a well-liked teacher, share the kind of relationship that truly, seriously, for the love of God cannot be real: that is, they're actually in love. Even after decades of marriage, parenting, and their own successful careers, their physical spark has somehow not diminished; in fact, they seem to relish the opportunity to share a single ice cream cone and drive others -- including their son, Charlie -- mad. Should it come as a surprise then that his own marriage is in crisis? But when Beth discovers that Don has been untruthful to her about his opinion of her work for years -- Beth's world comes crashing down. Has their whole relationship been one Big Fat Lie?

Characteristics.Producer:: Stefanie Azpiazu, Anthony Bregman, Nicole Holofcener, Julia Louis-Dreyfus

Reviews.Name: Brian Eggert
Reviews.Message: Holofcener accesses moving material that will make you laugh, possibly cry, and come away feeling a little wiser for it. Such modest pleasures at the cinema feel rare but vital.

Reviews.Name: Anthony Lane
Reviews.Message: Well, this setup might possibly furnish a single episode of “Seinfeld.” Whether it’s enough to sustain a whole movie is another matter.

Reviews.Name: Roger Moore
Reviews.Message: A twee...slight sociological study that takes navel-gazing New Yorkers into their AARP years, still comfortably discomfitted by the littlest things, still making mountains out of lives littered with molehills.

Reviews.Name: Erik Childress
Reviews.Message: Nicole Holofcener just does not miss and her reunion with Julia Louis-Dreyfus is one of her best in hilariously charting the perils of the damage that can be inflicted by false confidence and loving reassurance with characters who feel authentic.

Reviews.Name: Brian Rowe
Reviews.Message: You Hurt My Feelings is as good as Enough Said, if not better, and I hope she makes more films with Louis-Dreyfus. The two have a kinship that works beautifully on a narrative level...

Reviews.Name: Louisa Moore
Reviews.Message: Crackerjack writing and a talented cast make this very relatable (and funny) adult comedy-drama achieve its full potential.

Reviews.Name: Amber Wilkinson
Reviews.Message: An constant supply of quotable zingers lends energy to almost every scene

Reviews.Name: Martin Carr
Reviews.Message: Tried, tested, and uninspiring - this four way relationship drama goes over old ground.

Reviews.Name: Dennis Schwartz
Reviews.Message: Delivers with a light touch a well-observed drama.

Reviews.Name: Piers Marchant
Reviews.Message: Collectively, these exquisitely rendered moments begin to form a much greater whole, creating a sense of the world for [Nicole Holofcener's] characters that somehow expands far beyond what we actually see of them.

Reviews.Name: Juan Carlos Ugarelli
Reviews.Message: Through everyday life situations and seemingly trivial conversations, Holofcener's excellent screenplay and the spot-on performances of the cast explore the theme of personal realization with a sharp sense of humor. [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Rachel Wagner
Reviews.Message: Especially married couples will be able to relate to this story and its wonderful dialogue

Reviews.Name: Daniel Joyaux
Reviews.Message: What ensues is a poignant and funny investigation into the little lies of encouragement we spout to our loved ones and the damage it can do when those built-up fibs are suddenly revealed.

Reviews.Name: Zoë Rose Bryant
Reviews.Message: It’s tender, terrifically funny, and endlessly thought-provoking, and it sends you out on a heartfelt high with new knowledge to apply to your own life, so you learn from Beth and Don’s miscommunications instead of repeating their mistakes yourself.

Reviews.Name: Andrea Thompson
Reviews.Message: It might be Holofcener’s most tender portrayal yet of a woman whose world is upended just as she’s at a critical crossroads in her life.

Reviews.Name: Brian Tallerico
Reviews.Message: One of [Holofcener's] smartest and funniest films.

Reviews.Name: Ross Bonaime
Reviews.Message: You Hurt My Feelings is the type of film that reminds us why Holofcener is one of the best writers of comedies today, and that her ability to write films with such small consequences can often feel like a massive achievement.

Reviews.Name: Pat Mullen
Reviews.Message: The film marks Holofcener's best work since 2010’s Please Give for its warm, witty, and wise consideration of relationships.

Reviews.Name: Frank J. Avella
Reviews.Message: It's bracing to have a relationship dramedy that is not centered on infidelity, but about the way we as humans are so simultaneously fragile and narcissistic.

Reviews.Name: Alissa Wilkinson
Reviews.Message: The resulting film is warm-hearted and rueful and hilarious in all the best ways.

Reviews.Message: Collectively, these exquisitely rendered moments begin to form a much greater whole, creating a sense of the world for [Nicole Holofcener's] characters that somehow expands far beyond what we actually see of them.

Reviews.Name: Juan Carlos Ugarelli
Reviews.Message: Through everyday life situations and seemingly trivial conversations, Holofcener's excellent screenplay and the spot-on performances of the cast explore the theme of personal realization with a sharp sense of humor. [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Rachel Wagner
Reviews.Message: Especially married couples will be able to relate to this story and its wonderful dialogue

Reviews.Name: Daniel Joyaux
Reviews.Message: What ensues is a poignant and funny investigation into the little lies of encouragement we spout to our loved ones and the damage it can do when those built-up fibs are suddenly revealed.

Reviews.Name: Zoë Rose Bryant
Reviews.Message: It’s tender, terrifically funny, and endlessly thought-provoking, and it sends you out on a heartfelt high with new knowledge to apply to your own life, so you learn from Beth and Don’s miscommunications instead of repeating their mistakes yourself.

Reviews.Name: Andrea Thompson
Reviews.Message: It might be Holofcener’s most tender portrayal yet of a woman whose world is upended just as she’s at a critical crossroads in her life.

Reviews.Name: Brian Tallerico
Reviews.Message: One of [Holofcener's] smartest and funniest films.

Reviews.Name: Ross Bonaime
Reviews.Message: You Hurt My Feelings is the type of film that reminds us why Holofcener is one of the best writers of comedies today, and that her ability to write films with such small consequences can often feel like a massive achievement.

Reviews.Name: Pat Mullen
Reviews.Message: The film marks Holofcener's best work since 2010’s Please Give for its warm, witty, and wise consideration of relationships.

Reviews.Name: Frank J. Avella
Reviews.Message: It's bracing to have a relationship dramedy that is not centered on infidelity, but about the way we as humans are so simultaneously fragile and narcissistic.

Reviews.Name: Alissa Wilkinson
Reviews.Message: The resulting film is warm-hearted and rueful and hilarious in all the best ways.

Title: The Wrath of Becky
Description: Two years after she escaped a violent attack on her family, Becky attempts to rebuild her life in the care of an older woman -- a kindred spirit named Elena. But when a group known as the "Noble Men" break into their home, attack them, and take her beloved dog, Diego, Becky must return to her old ways to protect herself and her loved ones.

Characteristics.Production Co:: Media Finance Capital, Yale Productions, Post Film, Fluffy Bear Studios, RainMaker Films, BoulderLight Pictures, Quiver Distribution

Reviews.Name: Dan Scully
Reviews.Message: Delivers on strong thematic and character work, while also providing no shortage of splattery, cathartic violence to boot.

Reviews.Name: MontiLee Stormer
Reviews.Message: Campy fun? Yes. Ultra-violent? You bet! What separates Becky is that it’s not aiming for the “comedy” part of horror comedy. It’s organically funny and while the situations are off the wall, the natural progression of the storyline isn’t.

Reviews.Name: Dolores Quintana
Reviews.Message: THE WRATH OF BECKY is a serviceable film with some decent gore, but it has some ideas you have already seen before.

Reviews.Name: Drew Tinnin
Reviews.Message: Wrath of Becky is much more than a fantasy revenge tale about getting even with white trash nationalists and dumb-witted domestic terrorists.It’s an official coming out party for star-in-the-making Lulu Wilson.

Reviews.Name: Dustin Rowles
Reviews.Message: The tone of the sequel is more cartoonish than the original -- the lighting is brighter and the blood is redder -- but it’s no less satisfying.

Reviews.Name: Brian Tallerico
Reviews.Message: There’s a charming simplicity to a genre film that can be introduced as “Let’s just kill some fascists!” and Angel & Coote know how to pace and deliver this kind of gut punch of a movie.

Reviews.Name: Dennis Schwartz
Reviews.Message: The cheeky film has the same fiery revenge tone as the original even with new directors and writers.

Reviews.Name: J Hurtado
Reviews.Message: If the first film was Home Alone, this one is a bit more John Wick, only with less martial arts and more exploding fascist rednecks, and that is totally cool with me.

Reviews.Name: Anton Bitel
Reviews.Message: Becky’s need for teen kicks delivers enough delinquent destruction of Nazis to bring bloody satisfaction.

Reviews.Name: Martin Unsworth
Reviews.Message: Outrageously over the top, The Wrath of Becky goes against the grain when it comes to sequels – particularly when they don’t contain input from the core behind-the-scenes crew – in that it’s even more fun than the original.

Reviews.Name: Dan Tabor
Reviews.Message: Wrath of Becky is a blood-drenched blast from start to finish and the perfect film for any genre fan looking for a bit of that ultraviolence.

Reviews.Name: Matt Donato
Reviews.Message: A fun-filled slaughter-fest.

Reviews.Name: Nathaniel Muir
Reviews.Message: The Wrath of Becky manages to bring everything together and never feels like the importance of the issues are being downplayed. The villains are an immediate threat to Becky, but they will also be recognizable to audiences.

Reviews.Name: Meagan Navarro
Reviews.Message: Angel and Coote’s playful tonal shift becomes instrumental in the sequel’s success as an entertaining action-horror-comedy romp, and Wilson is more than game in taking Becky less seriously. It makes for an irreverently delightful time.

Reviews.Name: Kat Hughes
Reviews.Message: Lulu Wilson’s Becky is always a fun character to spend time with, but despite the best efforts of all involved, The Wrath of Becky pales in comparison to what came before.

Title: The Hole in the Fence
Description: At a secluded exclusive summer camp in the Mexican countryside, under the watchful eyes of their adult guardians, boys from a prestigious private school receive physical, moral and religious training to turn them into tomorrow's elite. The discovery of a hole in the fence sets in motion a chain of disturbing events as the boys devolve into a Lord of the Flies-like mob mentality that creates and spreads hysteria in this profoundly disturbing coming-of-age drama that unravels like a horror movie while drawing on actual events.

Characteristics.Producer:: Fernanda De la Peza

Reviews.Name: Hugo Lara
Reviews.Message: [Del Paso] maximizes his main location, a place in the middle of the forest, filmed with an atmosphere that suddenly recharges with psychological terror... [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Javier Perez
Reviews.Message: Lacks a dramatic anchor to bond with the audience despite some unsettling dramatic flashes and tensions. [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Alejandro Alemán
Reviews.Message: Del Paso reinforces his ability to portray chaos, and through its montage, have fear and indignation invade us. [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Carlos Bonfil
Reviews.Message: An intelligent thriller, with agile rhythm, stupendous artistry in photography and sound, and a polarizing theme that is open to discourse. [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Erick Estrada
Reviews.Message: The Hole in the Fence is a story that captures [the essence of] what you read about in the papers. [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Fernanda Solórzano
Reviews.Message: The Hole in the Fence manages to build a sinister universe that, on the one hand, is close to us and, on the other, is inserted into a vein of horror mythology. [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Carson Timar
Reviews.Message: It is hard to argue against The Hole in the Fence being anything but one of the best films of the year.

Reviews.Name: Vassilis Kroustallis

Reviews.Name: Israel Acosta Aroche
Reviews.Message: Joaquín del Paso brings us a provocative and shocking film that manages to mix elements of psychological terror and political criticism. [Full review in Spanish]

Title: Will-o'-the-Wisp
Description: On his deathbed, his royal highness Alfredo, King without a crown, is taken back to distant youth memories and the time he dreamt of becoming a fireman. The encounter with instructor Afonso from the fire brigade, opens a new chapter in the life of the two young men immersed in love and desire, and the will to change the status quo.

Reviews.Message: Rodrigues' musical fantasy is a fascinating cinematic challenge. [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Carlos Losilla
Reviews.Message: Contemplates reality as a delusion worth living and, therefore, as a privilege that no one has the right to take away from us. [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Amparo Cabal
Reviews.Message: A brief but fun and memorable film with a queer perspective and a very unique sense of humor. [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Jason Shawhan
Reviews.Message: [It] delivers ample amounts of firehouse choreography and dangling parts.

Reviews.Name: Ankit Jhunjhunwala
Reviews.Message: Above all functions as a love story, even though it has a lot of tricks up its sleeve.

Reviews.Name: Lee Jutton
Reviews.Message: It’s altogether hilarious and yet still heartfelt, extremely weird but wonderful regardless—just like the rest of Will-o’-the-Wisp.

Reviews.Name: Jason Adams
Reviews.Message: A beefcake fantasia of masculine camaraderie that’s spills into dance and forest-floor mutual masturbation

Reviews.Name: Juan Carlos Ugarelli

Reviews.Name: Matthew St. Clair
Reviews.Message: Rodrigues' ability to condense a myriad of genres into a small package is a grand feat.

Reviews.Name: Tomas Trussow
Reviews.Message: It bounces in the interstices of varying genres and critiques, undaunted by the fact that not every strike is cleanly wrought, but confident in being caustic when needed, while also giving satire a breath of much-needed fresh air.

Reviews.Name: Carlos Esquives
Reviews.Message: João Pedro Rodrigues isn't subtle in blaming repressions on colonialist heritage and in the process, he continues to pave way for diversity of expression in his homoerotic universe. [Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Kent Turner
Reviews.Message: Portuguese director João Pedro Rodrigues goes for it in the low-budget "Fogo-Fátuo," the most audacious, funniest, and unpredictable work seen at the 2022 Cannes Film Festival.

Reviews.Name: Guy Lodge
Reviews.Message: “Will-o’-the-Wisp” lives up to the flighty, elusive promise of its title, teasing its viewers in more ways than one...

Reviews.Name: Ryan Swen
Reviews.Message: Rodrigues’ concentration of his plot, his ability to elide the parts that would prevent this from taking full flight as a musical fantasy, preserves [Will-o'-the-Wisp's] strange and uncanny spell.

Reviews.Name: Leslie Felperin
Reviews.Message: Will light a lot of fires.

Reviews.Name: Jara Yáñez
Reviews.Message:
A fun celebration, sophisticated, intelligent, and rich in art… containing a powerful political potency. 
[Full review in Spanish]

Reviews.Name: Allan Hunter
Reviews.Message: Served up with lashings of homoeroticism, Bunuelian satire, a gay love story and an athletic dance number, its uncompromising nature will delight fans of the visionary filmmaker.

Reviews.Name: Charles Bramesco
Reviews.Message: A man on his deathbed recounts his youth as a firefighter in João Pedro Rodrigues' queer feature.

Title: Close to Vermeer
Description: Go behind the scenes of the largest Vermeer exhibition ever mounted, now on view at the Rijksmuseum in Amsterdam. Capturing the imagination of the art world -- with glowing reviews, global publicity, and tickets sold out through the entirety of its run -- the Rijksmuseum's Vermeer retrospective is nothing short of an historic event. Suzanne Raes's film follows curators, conservators, collectors, and experts in their joint mission to shine a new light on the elusive Dutch Master. This fascinating documentary reveals everything from the quiet diplomacy required to get the Vermeers to the Netherlands and the new technical knowledge gained by scanning the paintings layer by layer, to the shocking news that one work may not be by Vermeer after all. In the process, we discover how Vermeer was able to depict reality so differently from his contemporaries. But above all, Close to Vermeer shows the infectious love Vermeer's art inspires. As one curator lovingly puts it: "A good exhibition should change your view of the world. Vermeer can really do that."

Characteristics.Producer:: Ilja Roomans

Title: White Balls on Walls
Description: Amsterdam's Stedelijk Museum of Modern Art wants to become more diverse and inclusive. But how to go about that? An honest look behind the scenes into the sometimes-fraught process taking place in many public institutions.

Characteristics.Producer:: Elize Kerseboom, Frank van den Engel

Reviews.Name: Sarah Gopaul
Reviews.Message: This is a surprisingly candid portrayal of an organization striving to be better and recognizing that embracing their discomfort is the only way to move forward.

Title: MobKing

Title: Spider-Man: Across the Spider-Verse

Description: World War I has ended and Italian soldiers, broken but victorious, are returning to an impoverished village ruled by wealthy landowners. As events surrounding the first free election in Italy threaten to tear the village apart, Padre Pio struggles with his own personal demons, ultimately emerging from his spiritual anguish to become one of Catholicism's most venerated figures.

Title: Lynch/Oz
Description: The themes, images, and cultural vernacular of Victor Fleming's The Wizard of Oz continue to haunt David Lynch's art and filmography -- from his very first short, The Alphabet, to his latest series, Twin Peaks: The Return. Arguably, no filmmaker has so consistently drawn inspiration -- consciously or unconsciously -- from a single work. Is David Lynch trapped in the land of Oz? If so, can we derive a new appreciation for Lynch's body of work from taking a closer look at how it intersects and communicates with The Wizard of Oz? In turn, do Mulholland Drive, Lost Highway or The Elephant Man have something to say about the enduring resonance of America's most beloved holiday movie? Through six distinct perspectives, and narrated by some of contemporary cinema's most exciting voices, LYNCH/OZ will take us down the proverbial rabbit hole, help us re-experience and re-interpret The Wizard of Oz by way of David Lynch, to deliver a whole new appreciation for Lynch's symbolism through the lens of his greatest influence.

Characteristics.Writer:: Alexandre O. Philippe, Alexandre O. Philippe

Reviews.Name: Carmen Paddock
Reviews.Message: The result is a full-scale celebration of beautifully rendered images that invites further independent exploration.

Reviews.Name: Rich Cline
Reviews.Message: Cleverly weaving in hundreds of clips, filmmaker Alexandre O Philippe finds fascinating parallels everywhere, and especially in the films of David Lynch. Set out in idiosyncratic chapters, it's essential viewing for movie fans.

Reviews.Name: Linda Marric
Reviews.Message: An absolute must

Reviews.Name: Alistair Harkness
Reviews.Message: Philippe attempts to use The Wizard of Oz’s status as the foundational fairytale of American pop culture to decode this most playfully cryptic of filmmakers.

Reviews.Name: Danny Leigh
Reviews.Message: ... Anyone who calls themselves a film lover should have a working knowledge of perhaps the last true artist in American movies. And from his niche, Philippe has universal lessons about the nature of influence.

Reviews.Name: Maria Lattila
Reviews.Message: At the heart of Lynch/Oz is a deep love of the auteur’s work from Philippe and his contributors. This genuine fascination is what makes Lynch/Oz exciting and so compelling.

Reviews.Name: Marina Ashioti
Reviews.Message: Varied, compelling and evocative explorations of Lynch’s craft and thought processes.

Reviews.Name: Peter Bradshaw
Reviews.Message: At all events, it’s a very enjoyable creative speculation.

Reviews.Name: Michael Talbot-Haynes
Reviews.Message: There is more grasping of straws here than when they were trying to put the scarecrow back together.

Reviews.Name: Drew Tinnin
Reviews.Message: The documentary Lynch/Oz is a hypnotic deep dive into David Lynch’s fascination (or obsession) with The Wizard of Oz. Looking at all of his films through the lens of the 1939 classic provides tremendous insight into Lynch’s oeuvre.

Reviews.Name: Jason Gorber
Reviews.Message: This is a documentary that beautifully fosters critical discourse while also, with every shot, reminding about what a magical experience truly loving a cinematic work can be.

Reviews.Name: Martyn Conterio
Reviews.Message: What Philippe does yet again, as with his his previous documentaries, is a bang-up job of examining what makes great films great, and here it is twofold.

Reviews.Name: Andrew Murray
Reviews.Message: Lynch/Oz is...a grand love letter to cinema as much as it is to Lynch.

Reviews.Name: Richard Whittaker
Reviews.Message: Even its flaws and occasional moments of repetition between authors cannot detract from this fascinating collection about one of the great filmmakers of our era.

Reviews.Name: Caitlyn Downs
Reviews.Message: Alexandre O. Philippe continues to deliver absorbing studies of his subjects, accompanied by a host of creatives.

Reviews.Name: Alan French
Reviews.Message: Few of us would guess that the nightmarish realities constructed by the auteur David Lynch could relate to The Wizard of Oz. When dissected by many of the most brilliant minds of the film industry, the parallels and ideals reverberate throughout each.

Reviews.Name: Greg Carlson
Reviews.Message: Philippe strikes a balance between the mesmerizing, endlessly fascinating constructions of the David Lynch Cinematic Universe and the durability of the powerful spell on moviemaking enjoyed for decades by The Wizard of Oz.

Reviews.Name: Milana Vujkov
Reviews.Message: [Director Alexandre O.] Philippe is turning out to be a virtuoso in translating cinematic sorcery into cultural code, firmly positioned on those ever-so-potent crossroads of zeitgeist and cinema.

Reviews.Name: Diego Batlle
Reviews.Message: Even though the accumulation of quotes and the waterfall of ideas can overwhelm at times, Lynch/Oz is a fascinating experience: visually hypnotic, challenging, and intellectually admirable. [Full review in Spanish]
